common_note.text: 2.4GHz Legacy power levels are based upon 0dB margin of compliance when testing a BCM94318MPGSG sample. 5GHz Legacy power levels are based upon 0dB margin of compliance when testing a BCM94309MP Rev 10.1 sample MIMO 2x2 power levels are based upon 0dB margin of compliance when testing a BCM94321MC/CB.
Conducted peak power is not antenna specific.

EU 2.4GHz spurious emissions have never been performed >16dBm conducted power prior to BCM94321MC/CB. BCM94321MC/CB products are compliant re: emissions up to >19dBm conducted power per TX chain. EU 5GHz spurious emissions have never been performed >17dBm conducted power prior toBCM94321MC/CB. BCM94321MC/CB products are compliant re: emissions up to >18dBm conducted power Legacy SISO and >19dBm composite for 2x2 MIMO transmit. Further work is required on a product specific basis.
Global countries can be based upon either FCC power (e.g. locale 9 ) or EU power requirements. Increased power settings only apply to channels 149-165.
Band references are as follows. 5.15-5.25 = Lower band (LB) 5.25-5.35 = Middle band (MB) 5.470-5.725 = European Middle Band (EMB) 5.725-5.850 - Upper Band (UB)

For Japan country code, STA uses JP and AP uses J2.
EIRP is equal to conducted power + antenna gain. "Conducted" power does not include antenna gain.
Based upon a Maximum 2x2 antenna gain of 3.9dBi @ 2.4GHz. To meet PSD the Max conducted MIMO 2x2 power is 20dBm for 20MHz TX (i.e with <0dBi antenna) and 18dBm for 40MHz TX (i.e. <2dBi antenna)
Based upon a Maximum 2x2 antenna gain of 7.44dBi @ 5GHz. To meet PSD the Max conducted MIMO 2x2 power is 20dBm for 20MHz/40MHz TX (i.e with <6dBi antenna). Assumption is no FCC 8dB easement.

Where the CDD (2Tx) power levels are less than 8dBm, then the assumption is that the equivalent SISO power will always be selected in the driver. Anywhere CDD (3Tx) power is less than 8dBm, then either CDD (3Tx)must be disabled or an alternate transmission mode will be selected. Anywhere CDD power is less than 8dBm, then either CDD must be disabled or an alternate transmission mode will be selected.
Assumption is no FCC 8dB easement.
MIMO is not allowed

11a/g CDD mode can be used "in countries that support MIMO" as long as the power/stream is tuned down to less than or equal to the worst case 11n 20MHz mode power level (worst case MCS0, CDD mode).This note is specific to 20MHz signaling. In countries that do NOT support MIMO the power defined in the Legacy a/g tables must be adhered to.
Power over MCS index only applies to 40MHz.
20MHz SISO power level covered by testing to legacy a/g modes.
The FCC approval is antenna type specific and the power must be limited as per the following locale/type. Locale An1-T1 = Stamp Metal antenna, Locale An1-T2 = PCB antenna
CDD mode not supported in for 20MHz transmittion in the 5150-5250MHz band.

For 5250-5350MHz band, the following applies: CDD mode (MCS 0-7) must be disabled for 20MHz transmission. MCS0-7 SISO needs to be set to the same power levels as Legacy 11a. MCS8-15 SDM needs to be set to 9dBm as per locale.
Port0 (main antenna) and port1 (aux antenna) power levels are based upon X17 SAR compliance.
For FCC MIMO locales, CH36-48 MIMO mode is typically disabled to allow for coherency requirements and associated low conducted TX power.
The above power mapping applies to both SISO and MIMO transmission modes.
FCC ONLY: In some 20in80/160 cases (example 3Tx high antenna gain) CDD mode power may be disabled in the driver. In this case use power defined for 20MHz STBC.
TW ONLY: In some 20in80 cases (example 3Tx high antenna gain) CDD mode power may be disabled in the driver. In this case use power defined for 20MHz STBC.
The 40in80 definition above is based upon known 20/40Tx characteristics against regulatory limits. Testing is needed to verify the above.
The above are the best case (highest) power mappings based upon testing a single 20,40,80MHz mode for regulatory. Additional differentiation and power maximization would require more testing.

Where "Lower of " two BW modes is defined this is due to cases where there are more than one regulatory limitation that may apply (typically involving FCC band edge restrictions and some other limit). The band edge would be product specific and in this case we may need to be more intelligent than just a fixed rule.
